This file compares the available useful parameters of the libraries PiCamera2 and OpenCV.

PiCamera2:
rpi.black_level     -    Specifies a default black level value to use for all three RGB channels
rpi.dpc             -	 Defective Pixel Correction
rpi.lux             -	 The values are derived from one of the Macbeth Chart calibration images
rpi.noise           -	 Calculate the noise profile of the image
rpi.geq             -	 Green Equalisation
rpi.sdn             -	 Spatial Denoise
rpi.awb             -	 Automatic White Balance
rpi.agc             -	 Automatic Gain Control
rpi.alsc            -	 Automatic Lens Shading Correction
rpi.contrast        -	 Contrast
rpi.ccm             -	 Colour Correction Matrices
rpi.sharpen         -	 Sharpening

= 12


OpenCV:
cv2.CAP_PROP_FRAME_WIDTH  -     Width
cv2.CAP_PROP_FRAME_HEIGHT -     Height
cv2.CAP_PROP_BRIGHTNESS   -     Brightness of the image (only for those cameras that support)
cv2.CAP_PROP_CONTRAST     -     Contrast of the image (only for cameras)
cv2.CAP_PROP_SATURATION   -     Saturation of the image (only for cameras)
cv2.CAP_PROP_HUE          -     Hue of the image (only for cameras)
cv2.CAP_PROP_GAIN         -     Gain of the image (only for those cameras that support)
cv2.CAP_PROP_EXPOSURE     -     Exposure (only for those cameras that support)
cv2.CAP_PROP_SHARPNESS    - 	/
cv2.CAP_PROP_AUTO_EXPOSURE-	DC1394: exposure control done by camera, user can adjust reference level using this feature
cv2.CAP_PROP_GAMMA        - 	/
cv2.CAP_PROP_TEMPERATURE  - 	/
cv2.CAP_PROP_ZOOM         - 	/
cv2.CAP_PROP_FOCUS        - 	/
cv2.CAP_PROP_BACKLIGHT    - 	/
cv2.CAP_PROP_AUTOFOCUS    - 	/
cv2.CAP_PROP_AUTO_WB      -     Enable/disable auto white-balance
cv2.CAP_PROP_WB_TEMPERATURE -   White-balance color temperature

= 16 (excluding width and height, which can be set also in PiCamera2)







